   "source": [
    "Linear algebra\n",
    "==============\n",
    "\n",
    "Silent substitution problems may be solved with linear algebra."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ac84d51-9b64-4264-be18-122919fffa4c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Basic example\n",
    "-------------"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "62f885b4-d9e9-4524-9741-a022aa8c49a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "************************************************************\n",
      "*************** Silent Substitution Problem ****************\n",
      "************************************************************\n",
      "Device: BCGAR (8-bit, linear)\n",
      "Ignoring: ['R']\n",
      "Minimising: ['M', 'L', 'I']\n",
      "Modulating: ['S']\n",
      "Background: [0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5]\n",
      "Target contrast: 0.2\n",
      "\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x288 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from pysilsub.problems import SilentSubstitutionProblem as SSP\n",
    "\n",
    "# Instantiate the problem class\n",
    "ssp = SSP.from_json('../../data/BCGAR.json')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define problem\n",
    "ssp.ignore = ['R']\n",
    "ssp.modulate = ['S']\n",
    "ssp.minimize = ['M', 'L', 'I']\n",
    "ssp.background = [.5] * ssp.nprimaries\n",
    "ssp.target_contrast = .2\n",
    "ssp.print_problem()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Find solution\n",
    "solution = ssp.linalg_solve()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot solution\n",
    "fig = ssp.plot_solution(solution)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "id": "e5cae925-abf5-4245-8b1e-0df39d21f873",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "The background settings are: [127, 127, 127, 127, 127]\n",
      "The modulation settings are: [205, 79, 128, 130, 98]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(f'The background settings are: {ssp.w2s(ssp.background)}')\n",
    "print(f'The modulation settings are: {ssp.w2s(solution)}')"
   ]
  },
  {

   "source": [
    "Now, the unique scaling coefficients for the primaries $\\alpha_{sc} = [p_{0} \\ p_{1} \\ p_{2} \\ p_{3} \\ p_{4}]$ that must be added to the primary weights for the background $\\alpha_{bg}$ for a requested modulation $\\beta = [S \\ M \\ L \\ R \\ I]$, are discovered as $\\alpha_{sc} = \\beta A^{-1}$."
   ]
  },

    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate inverse of A\n",
    "A1 = pd.DataFrame(\n",
    "    np.linalg.inv(A.values),\n",
    "    A.columns, \n",
    "    A.index)\n",
    "A1"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "66681fd3-f1b8-4c08-9175-c6e55897ee6a",

   ],
   "source": [
    "# Requested modulation for S-cones\n",
    "requested_contrast = .2\n",
    "\n",
    "b = np.array([requested_contrast, 0., 0., 0., 0.])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Scale requested contrasts to percentage of background units\n",
    "b = A.sum(axis=1).mul(b)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calculate the scaling coefficients\n",
    "asc = A1.dot(b) / 2\n",
    "asc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "aa2f6519-0362-4f31-9952-84e873eb1578",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d9692b66-303a-483c-8818-1ebf34664532",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Contrast modulations\n",
    "--------------------\n",
    "\n",
    "Multiprimary devices with good linearity, high resolution and rapid spectral switching capability may be used to present temporal modulations of photoreceptor-targeted contrast. Such stimuli have helped to shed light on how the pupil responds to input from different photoreceptors as a function of time (e.g., [Barrionuevo et al., 2016](https://jov.arvojournals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2565122); [Spitschan et al., 2014](https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1400942111)). \n",
    "\n",
    "To make contrast modulations, first define a stimulus profile with a sampling frequency in line with the switching capability of the stimulation device. In this case, its a 1 Hz sinusoid with 50 samples per cycle.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "8250cf7a-e57e-4450-af84-736170b3372d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "def sinusoid_modulation(f, duration, Fs=50):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Generate a sinusoidal waveform\"\"\"\n",
    "    x = np.arange(duration * Fs)\n",
    "    return np.sin(2 * np.pi * f * x / Fs)\n",
    "\n",
    "stimulus_profile = sinusoid_modulation(1, 1)\n",
    "time = np.linspace(0, 1000, 50).astype('int')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(time, stimulus_profile)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Time (ms)');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "967d7d77-e8f3-4089-82e1-2e6d9ef1a83b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, define a problem. Here we define the background spectrum as all primaries at half-max power so we can maximise bidirectional contrast. Then we say that we want to ignore rods, minimize contrast on M-cones, L-cones and melanopsin, and modulate the S-cones."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "c94214c2-fbc5-4a5e-907e-544d8cb56a64",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "************************************************************\n",
      "*************** Silent Substitution Problem ****************\n",
      "************************************************************\n",
      "Device: STLAB_1 (binocular, left eye)\n",
      "Ignoring: ['R']\n",
      "Minimising: ['M', 'L', 'I']\n",
      "Modulating: ['S']\n",
      "Background: [0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5]\n",
      "Target contrast: None\n",
      "\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Load some example data for a 10-primary system\n",
    "ssp = SSP.from_json('../../data/STLAB_1_York.json')\n",
    "\n",
    "ssp.background = [.5] * ssp.nprimaries\n",
    "ssp.ignore = ['R']\n",
    "ssp.minimize = ['M', 'L', 'I']\n",
    "ssp.modulate = ['S']\n",
    "ssp.print_problem()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1839fda0-795e-4bf7-b55c-8c99ee2fd31d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, choose a peak contrast value that is known to be in gamut and solve for each point in the stimulus profile. The algebraic approach is well suited here as it guarantees a linear uni-directional scaling of the primaries and is less computationally expensive than optimisation. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "64b3aec7-d53f-4a12-a6dc-bc4b0f2ede43",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "peak_contrast = .2  # Known to be within gamut\n",
    "solutions = []\n",
    "for point in stimulus_profile:\n",
    "    ssp.target_contrast = point * peak_contrast\n",
    "    solutions.append(ssp.linalg_solve())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6ca18c15-eb37-45c4-b8c1-bb3bbfa008fd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Plotting the forward projection of contrast for each solution in this case reveals a smooth S-cone modulation with little contrast splatter on the other photoreceptors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "1ae6aac2-0ddf-4ab7-b010-3d84f8d0abbf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "splatter = [ssp.get_photoreceptor_contrasts(s) for s in solutions]\n",
    "splatter = pd.concat(splatter, axis=1)    \n",
    "\n",
    "for r, s in splatter.iterrows():\n",
    "    ax.plot(time, s, label=r, color=ssp.aopic_colors[r])\n",
    "        \n",
    "    ax.set_ylabel('Simple contrast')\n",
    "    ax.set_title(ssp.name)\n",
    "    ax.set_xlabel('Time (s)')\n",
    "    \n",
    "plt.legend();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5498a363-62bd-48c8-a3dc-7610eeb9c3dd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Finally, convert the solutions to settings compatible with the native resolution of the stimulation device."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "c042708c-66b6-4838-a096-306b9320529b",
   "metadata": {},

   "source": [
    "device_settings = [ssp.w2s(s) for s in solutions]\n",
    "device_settings = pd.DataFrame(device_settings, index=time)\n",
    "with pd.option_context('display.max_rows', 10):\n",
    "    print(device_settings)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e5cfbf58-a16d-49dc-b6ec-a2ac17ecc260",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now you just need to tell the stimulation device to set the primary inputs to these values at the specified timepoints and it will produce the S-cone modulation shown above. \n",
    "\n",
    "Note that with this method one can also modulate multiple photoreceptors together."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "6f1e97d4-a638-4e6a-adb0-82e002517418",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ssp.ignore = ['R']\n",
    "ssp.minimize = ['I']\n",
    "ssp.modulate = ['S', 'M', 'L']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "3f0667ad-f803-49e3-97ac-07d8373842b0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "peak_contrast = .2  # Known to be within gamut\n",
    "solutions = []\n",
    "for point in stimulus_profile:\n",
    "    ssp.target_contrast = point * peak_contrast\n",
    "    solutions.append(ssp.linalg_solve())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "0c13be8c-01df-483e-ac02-6dddad665717",

   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "splatter = [ssp.get_photoreceptor_contrasts(s) for s in solutions]\n",
    "splatter = pd.concat(splatter, axis=1)    \n",
    "\n",
    "for r, s in splatter.iterrows():\n",
    "    ax.plot(time, s, label=r, color=ssp.aopic_colors[r])\n",

    "    \n",
    "plt.legend();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "790d0ad6-f791-40a9-9468-bd23ac30ff26",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can even modulate photoreceptors in counterphase."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "a048416d-0f09-4a7f-b5c0-fde9039ebce4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

    "    solutions.append(ssp.linalg_solve())"
   ]
